{'content_type': 'audio_transcription', 'text': 'Yeah, it does sound kind of magical, right? The yeast actually just comes naturally from the environment. Teff flour has natural wild yeasts and bacteria that kind of do the whole fermentation job for you once you mix it with water. So, it’s really as simple as just letting it hang out for a bit.

Now, in terms of timing, one to two days is usually a sweet spot. But if you let it go longer, it can get a little more sour and develop more flavor. Some people do that on purpose. But usually a day or two is enough to get a nice mild tang.

And yeah, if you’re doing it at a restaurant or making a lot of it, they’ll often have different batches going at different stages—kind of like a little injera fermentation rotation. So one batch is ready today, another is fermenting for tomorrow, and they just keep that cycle going. That way, they’ve always got a steady supply of fresh injera.', 'direction': 'out', 'decoding_id': None}
